Description: A pyramidal double-ended stamp, pierced from side to side with a circular suspension-hole. On the largest end, which is oblong, is a circular depression above a circle (?) (one side is broken away) flanked by a branch-pattern. At the opposite end is a square containing a chevron, impressed with a gamma. Two of the edges are bevelled (one damaged); on the side opposite the face with bevelled edges is an ankh-cross flanked by the letters epsilon and rho. All decoration is incuse and cut into the leather-hard clay. Brown Nile silt, with a buff surface in places.
Curator's comments: Terracotta IV Donated: Egypt Exploration Fund. Excavated at Oxyrhynchus. Probably Roman period, but it may be earlier.
Bibliographic references: Terracotta / Catalogue of Terracottas in the British Museum (3600)
